1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,311
A new model launches.

2
00:00:01,311 --> 00:00:03,607
It scores zero point three points higher

3
00:00:03,607 --> 00:00:05,902
than its predecessor on a respected benchmark.

4
00:00:05,902 --> 00:00:08,198
The slide shows two bars almost touching,

5
00:00:08,198 --> 00:00:10,165
with the new one nudging ahead.

6
00:00:10,165 --> 00:00:12,461
The press release calls it "state of

7
00:00:12,461 --> 00:00:14,756
the art." Tweets call it "the next

8
00:00:14,756 --> 00:00:17,051
leap." A zero point three point gap.

9
00:00:17,051 --> 00:00:20,331
Today I want to take that zero point three apart.

10
00:00:20,331 --> 00:00:22,626
Not to call any specific lab dishonest

11
00:00:22,626 --> 00:00:24,922
— I'm not here for that —

12
00:00:24,922 --> 00:00:26,561
but to walk you through,

13
00:00:26,561 --> 00:00:28,857
with my own numbers, how much of

14
00:00:28,857 --> 00:00:31,152
a small benchmark gap can come from

15
00:00:31,152 --> 00:00:34,103
things that aren't the model getting better at all.

16
00:00:34,103 --> 00:00:36,734
This is the bar chart you saw.

17
00:00:36,734 --> 00:00:37,485
Two numbers.

18
00:00:37,485 --> 00:00:38,236
One taller.

19
00:00:38,236 --> 00:00:39,739
Now look at this.

20
00:00:39,739 --> 00:00:42,369
Last time, I reran one benchmark ten

21
00:00:42,369 --> 00:00:45,000
times and got scores between eighty-nine point

22
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:46,878
one and ninety-three point eight.

23
00:00:46,878 --> 00:00:49,508
That's a spread of four point seven

24
00:00:49,508 --> 00:00:51,763
points — on a single model.

25
00:00:51,763 --> 00:00:54,393
A zero point three point gap inside

26
00:00:54,393 --> 00:00:58,150
that envelope is statistical noise wearing the hat of progress.

27
00:00:58,150 --> 00:01:00,780
So the very first thing the honest

28
00:01:00,780 --> 00:01:03,786
reader does is ask: where is the spread?

29
00:01:03,786 --> 00:01:06,792
Without it, you cannot tell signal from rerun.

30
00:01:06,792 --> 00:01:10,100
Let's grant the lab the benefit of the doubt.

31
00:01:10,100 --> 00:01:11,938
Both models ran ten times.

32
00:01:11,938 --> 00:01:13,409
The spreads were tight.

33
00:01:13,409 --> 00:01:17,085
The zero point three is real on this exact benchmark.

34
00:01:17,085 --> 00:01:18,188
What happens then?

35
00:01:18,188 --> 00:01:20,762
Then the question becomes: how much of

36
00:01:20,762 --> 00:01:24,070
that zero point three is the model being better,

37
00:01:24,070 --> 00:01:27,011
and how much is the measurement having moved?

38
00:01:27,012 --> 00:01:31,055
Because the measurement can move too — and I have receipts.

39
00:01:31,055 --> 00:01:33,224
On this channel, four episodes ago,

40
00:01:33,224 --> 00:01:36,115
I ran an experiment with frontier AI judges.

41
00:01:36,115 --> 00:01:38,644
Every judge graded the same forty answers

42
00:01:38,644 --> 00:01:41,174
twice — once with correct author labels,

43
00:01:41,174 --> 00:01:42,981
once with the labels flipped.

44
00:01:42,981 --> 00:01:45,149
The label is just a string.

45
00:01:45,149 --> 00:01:47,679
It tells you nothing about the response.

46
00:01:47,679 --> 00:01:49,124
The text is identical.

47
00:01:49,124 --> 00:01:52,738
But three of the four judges quietly changed their grade.

48
00:01:52,738 --> 00:01:55,629
The size of the swing varied by judge.

49
00:01:55,629 --> 00:01:59,604
The average, across the panel, was about zero point three points.

50
00:01:59,604 --> 00:02:00,688
Read that again.

51
00:02:00,688 --> 00:02:03,218
Just believing a different model wrote the

52
00:02:03,218 --> 00:02:06,470
response moved the grade by zero point three points.

53
00:02:06,470 --> 00:02:09,722
That is the same number as a typical headline.

54
00:02:09,722 --> 00:02:12,252
If both labs in our launch picture

55
00:02:12,252 --> 00:02:14,781
use the same family of AI judge,

56
00:02:14,781 --> 00:02:17,311
and the labels in the eval point

57
00:02:17,311 --> 00:02:19,841
to the new model — the gap

58
00:02:19,841 --> 00:02:21,648
could be the bias alone.

59
00:02:21,647 --> 00:02:24,753
Three episodes back I showed the same model,

60
00:02:24,753 --> 00:02:28,634
same questions, three formats: multiple choice scored ninety-two point four,

61
00:02:28,634 --> 00:02:32,516
free response eighty-four point one, and tool-use seventy-one point three.

62
00:02:32,516 --> 00:02:36,010
The format changes the score by about twenty points.

63
00:02:36,010 --> 00:02:40,279
Now imagine two labs choosing how to evaluate their own model.

64
00:02:40,279 --> 00:02:44,549
Lab A picks multiple choice — it scores their model high.

65
00:02:44,549 --> 00:02:48,431
Lab B picks free response — it scores theirs high.

66
00:02:48,431 --> 00:02:51,924
Both quote the format that makes them look better.

67
00:02:51,924 --> 00:02:53,477
This is not lying.

68
00:02:53,477 --> 00:02:56,194
It is "we picked the eval that

69
00:02:56,194 --> 00:02:58,911
best demonstrates capability," which is true and

70
00:02:58,911 --> 00:03:00,852
deceptive at the same time.

71
00:03:00,852 --> 00:03:03,569
A zero point three point headline gap

72
00:03:03,569 --> 00:03:06,287
can sit inside a twenty point format

73
00:03:06,287 --> 00:03:08,615
gap and tell you almost nothing.

74
00:03:08,615 --> 00:03:11,945
A benchmark is usually a mean over categories.

75
00:03:11,945 --> 00:03:12,777
Headline sixty-seven.

76
00:03:12,777 --> 00:03:13,610
Math twelve.

77
00:03:13,610 --> 00:03:14,442
Humanities eighty-five.

78
00:03:14,442 --> 00:03:18,604
If the launch press release leads with "best in humanities,

79
00:03:18,604 --> 00:03:21,517
eighty-five" or "leads on math by three

80
00:03:21,517 --> 00:03:24,014
points," ask which category they picked,

81
00:03:24,014 --> 00:03:26,511
and what the overall mean was,

82
00:03:26,511 --> 00:03:29,424
and where the other category went down.

83
00:03:29,424 --> 00:03:32,338
Subscores are the cheapest place to mine

84
00:03:32,338 --> 00:03:34,835
a zero point three point gap.

85
00:03:34,835 --> 00:03:38,580
Move one heavy category up by half a point,

86
00:03:38,580 --> 00:03:41,910
move two light categories down by a tenth,

87
00:03:41,910 --> 00:03:43,990
and the overall rounds up.

88
00:03:43,990 --> 00:03:45,655
The trick isn't fabrication.

89
00:03:45,655 --> 00:03:46,487
It's selection.

90
00:03:46,487 --> 00:03:49,021
So how do we account for a

91
00:03:49,021 --> 00:03:50,831
zero point three point headline?

92
00:03:50,831 --> 00:03:53,003
Let me draw a small budget.

93
00:03:53,003 --> 00:03:54,813
On the left, the gap.

94
00:03:54,813 --> 00:03:56,623
On the right, the candidates.

95
00:03:56,623 --> 00:03:59,157
Rerun noise: up to plus or minus

96
00:03:59,157 --> 00:04:01,328
two point three points — alone,

97
00:04:01,328 --> 00:04:04,586
large enough to swallow the zero point three whole.

98
00:04:04,586 --> 00:04:08,568
Grader bias from a same-family judge: about zero point three points.

99
00:04:08,568 --> 00:04:11,826
Format choice: zero point five to two points easily,

100
00:04:11,826 --> 00:04:14,359
depending on how different the chosen format

101
00:04:14,359 --> 00:04:16,169
is from the natural one.

102
00:04:16,169 --> 00:04:18,341
Subscore reweighting: one to three points,

103
00:04:18,341 --> 00:04:20,513
depending on how aggressive the slicing.

104
00:04:20,513 --> 00:04:23,047
These aren't certainties — they're upper bounds.

105
00:04:23,047 --> 00:04:25,581
When the lab documents none of them,

106
00:04:25,581 --> 00:04:28,114
the bound is what you have to

107
00:04:28,114 --> 00:04:29,924
assume could be in play.

108
00:04:29,924 --> 00:04:32,458
The "how much of this is the

109
00:04:32,458 --> 00:04:34,992
model" share — the bottom bar —

110
00:04:34,992 --> 00:04:37,526
can be as little as zero of

111
00:04:37,526 --> 00:04:39,336
the headline zero point three.

112
00:04:39,336 --> 00:04:43,252
This is not an argument that no benchmark gap is real.

113
00:04:43,252 --> 00:04:46,812
When a model gains five points across four different evals,

114
00:04:46,812 --> 00:04:49,660
in three different formats, with two different graders,

115
00:04:49,660 --> 00:04:52,152
with the spread reported and the slicing

116
00:04:52,151 --> 00:04:55,000
held constant — that is a real gain.

117
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:56,779
The honest threshold isn't zero.

118
00:04:56,780 --> 00:04:59,272
It is higher than the gap on

119
00:04:59,271 --> 00:05:01,764
the slide when the slide is uncalibrated.

120
00:05:01,764 --> 00:05:04,256
So next time you see a zero

121
00:05:04,256 --> 00:05:06,748
point three point headline, the first question

122
00:05:06,747 --> 00:05:09,240
isn't "is the new model better." The

123
00:05:09,240 --> 00:05:11,732
question is: "is zero point three even

124
00:05:11,732 --> 00:05:14,224
the kind of number that could tell

125
00:05:14,223 --> 00:05:18,139
us that?" Most of the time, the honest answer is no.

126
00:05:18,139 --> 00:05:19,919
The story behind the headline.
